  "prompt": "If India was a part of UNSC would it have been able to ban Masood Azhar without China's support?",
  "response": "No, India would not have been able to ban Masood Azhar at the United Nations Security Council (UNSC) without China's support, even if India itself were a permanent member of the UNSC. This is because of the veto power held by the five permanent members (P5) of the UNSC: the United States, the United Kingdom, France, Russia, and China.\n\nThe process of designating an individual as a global terrorist under the UNSC requires consensus among all P5 members. If any one of these members exercises its veto, the proposal will not pass, regardless of support from other members, including India. China, in particular, blocked multiple attempts to designate Masood Azhar, the leader of the Pakistan-based militant group Jaish-e-Mohammed, as a global terrorist, citing a lack of sufficient evidence. It was only in 2019, after extensive diplomatic efforts and compromises, that China lifted its technical hold, allowing Azhar to be designated as a global terrorist.\n\nEven if India were a permanent member, it would still need the support of the other P5 members, including China, to successfully impose such a ban. The veto power ensures that no single permanent member can unilaterally push through a decision without the agreement of the others.",
